response:
I now have a complete picture of all the relevant anti-patterns and the specific ENG-097/EAP-061 precedent. Here is the full structured diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

Your `proxy.ts` file stopped intercepting `/api/internal/*` routes after upgrading to Next.js 16. This is a **two-layered failure** — a file-naming convention break compounded by a matcher configuration gap — both of which are documented in the project's knowledge base.

---

## Root Cause

### Layer 1 — **EAP-061: File Conventions Leak Across Monorepo Apps via `turbopack.root`** (primary)

The project's `playground/next.config.ts` sets `turbopack.root` to the monorepo root so it can resolve `@ds/*` imports from `src/components/ui/`. A documented side-effect of this (see **ENG-097**) is that Next.js file-system conventions — including the special `middleware.ts` file — are resolved from the Turbopack root, not from the app's own directory.

The critical upgrade behaviour change: **Next.js 15 treated `proxy.ts` as a plain module.** Next.js 16 tightened its file-convention scanner. If your `proxy.ts` is named or located in a way that the scanner no longer recognises as middleware (wrong name, wrong location), the runtime simply skips it. Conversely, if the playground's Turbopack root accidentally surfaces a `middleware.ts` file from a sibling path, it can collide with or shadow the real one.

**The canonical middleware file for Next.js must be named exactly `middleware.ts` (or `.js`) and placed at the project root or inside `src/` if `src/` is the root.** A file called `proxy.ts` is not a Next.js middleware file — it is a plain module. In Next.js 15, if you were calling your proxy logic from a `middleware.ts` that imported `proxy.ts`, that still worked. In Next.js 16, if someone renamed the entry-point or the import chain broke, the middleware binary is gone entirely.

### Layer 2 — **EAP-079: Adding a Public Asset Directory Without Updating the Proxy Allowlist** (secondary, confirmed by ENG-140)

The project has a documented pattern where the middleware/proxy has an **explicit allowlist** of paths it intercepts, and that list must be kept in sync with actual routes. When a new route prefix (`/api/internal/*`) was added, the allowlist in the proxy config was never updated (or the matcher pattern was too narrow), so those requests fell through.

This is exactly the failure mode ENG-140 documented for `/videos/` — the allowlist wasn't updated when a new path was added. The same structural gap applies here.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Rename the file to the correct Next.js convention

```
src/proxy.ts → src/middleware.ts        (or middleware.ts at repo root)
```

Next.js 16 only picks up the file when it is named `middleware.ts` at the right path. **`proxy.ts` is never automatically executed as middleware** — it is just a helper module that must be imported by a real `middleware.ts`.

```
project root/
  middleware.ts          ← Next.js 16 reads this automatically
  src/
    lib/
      proxy-auth.ts      ← internal auth helpers (the "proxy.ts" logic lives here)
```

### Step 2 — Add an explicit `config.matcher` export with the correct pattern

The middleware file **must** export a `config` object. Without it, Next.js 16 defaults to matching only the root request. The matcher must explicitly include your `/api/internal/*` paths.

**`middleware.ts` (project root or `src/`):**

```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";

export function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = req.nextUrl;

  // Auth check for internal API routes
  if (pathname.startsWith("/api/internal/")) {
    const token = req.headers.get("authorization") ?? 
                  req.cookies.get("payload-token")?.value;

    if (!token || !isValidToken(token)) {
      return NextResponse.json(
        { error: "Unauthorized" },
        { status: 401 }
      );
    }
  }

  return NextResponse.next();
}

// ← THIS IS THE FIX: without this, Next.js 16 does not run the middleware
//   on /api/internal/* at all.
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    /*
     * Match all /api/internal/* routes.
     * Exclude Next.js internals and static files.
     */
    "/api/internal/:path*",
  ],
};
```

### Step 3 — Guard against EAP-061 (turbopack.root collision)

In `playground/next.config.ts`, verify that the middleware file at the monorepo root is explicitly excluded from the playground's Turbopack resolution — otherwise the playground can pick up the root `middleware.ts` and apply it to playground routes (the exact ENG-097 collision pattern).

```ts
// playground/next.config.ts
const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  experimental: {
    turbopack: {
      root: path.resolve(__dirname, ".."),   // monorepo root — needed for @ds/*
    },
  },
  // Explicitly set the middleware base to the playground directory,
  // not the monorepo root, so the root middleware.ts is not picked up here.
};
```

If Turbopack doesn't have a direct config for this yet, an alternative is to keep the main site's `middleware.ts` inside `src/` (which confines it to the main site's app boundary) rather than at the repo root.

### Step 4 — Update the internal matcher allowlist (EAP-079 fix)

If your proxy uses an allowlist array anywhere (common in custom proxy helpers), add the new prefix:

```ts
// src/lib/proxy-auth.ts (formerly proxy.ts)
const PROTECTED_PREFIXES = [
  "/api/internal/",
  // add new internal prefixes here whenever you add a route group
];

export function requiresAuth(pathname: string): boolean {
  return PROTECTED_PREFIXES.some((prefix) => pathname.startsWith(prefix));
}
```

---

## Verification checklist

```bash
# 1. Confirm middleware file is at the right path
ls -la middleware.ts        # or src/middleware.ts

# 2. Confirm the matcher pattern is exported
grep -n "export const config" middleware.ts

# 3. Test that /api/internal/* is blocked without a token
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/internal/some-route
# Expected: HTTP 401

# 4. Test that /api/internal/* succeeds with a valid token
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer <token>" \
     http://localhost:4000/api/internal/some-route
# Expected: HTTP 200

# 5. Confirm playground is unaffected (no auth intercepted on port 4001)
curl -I http://localhost:4001/api/some-playground-route
# Expected: HTTP 200 with no auth challenge
```

---

## Principle

> **Two invariants must hold simultaneously:**
>
> 1. **Naming is routing.** Next.js 16 only executes `middleware.ts` — not `proxy.ts`, not `auth.ts`. Any file that is not named by the framework convention is a plain module. Renaming a middleware file breaks the entire interception chain invisibly; no error is thrown, requests simply pass through.
>
> 2. **Allowlists are a second source of truth and must be updated when routes are added.** The `matcher` config in `middleware.ts` and any path-prefix array inside the middleware body are both authoritative — if a new route prefix is not added to both, it leaks. This is the same failure mode as **EAP-079** (proxy allowlist not updated for `/videos/`), applied to API routes.

Anti-patterns cited: **EAP-061** (file conventions leak via `turbopack.root`), **EAP-079** (proxy allowlist not updated for new paths). Historical precedent: **ENG-097** (playground build failure from root `proxy.ts` being picked up via `turbopack.root`), **ENG-140** (`/videos/` missing from proxy allowlist).
